Hello!

Thank you for this great library.

However, please consider adding a function to find if specified array includes all elements from another specified array.

Here's the related question on SO: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/8628059/check-if-every-element-in-one-array-is-in-a-second-array

Concept:

``` javascript

var array1 = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E'];
var array2 = ['B', 'C', 'E'];
var array3 = ['B', 'C', 'Z'];

_.includes(array1, array2); // => true
_.includes(array1, array3); // => false

```

Solution in vanilla JavaScript for modern browsers:

``` javascript
/**
 * Returns TRUE if the first specified array contains all elements
 * from the second one. FALSE otherwise.
 *
 * @param {array} superset
 * @param {array} subset
 *
 * @returns {boolean}
 */
function arrayContainsArray (superset, subset) {
  if (0 === subset.length) {
    return false;
  }
  return subset.every(function (value) {
    return (superset.indexOf(value) >= 0);
  });
}
```

Thank you!

The opposite of `_.where`. Instead of filtering each element in the array for items matching the source object, it filters items that _do not_ match the source object.

It could be called `_.exclude` but that might be confused with `_.include`.

For example:

``` js
var users = [
  { 'user': 'barney', 'age': 36, 'active': false, 'pets': ['hoppy'] },
  { 'user': 'fred',   'age': 40, 'active': true, 'pets': ['baby puss', 'dino'] }
];

_.pluck(_.exclude(users, { 'age': 36, 'active': false }), 'user');
// → ['fred']

_.pluck(_.exclude(users, { 'pets': ['dino'] }), 'user');
// → ['barney']
```

It would be handy if the `size` method could automatically check if the collection provided to it exists.

For example:

```
var foo = {};
console.log(_.size(foo.bar)); // undefined, and returns 0
console.log(_.size(foo.bar.baz)); // undefined, but JS errors out: TypeError: foo.bar is undefined
```

This is the typical workflow for checking the size of a nested object:

```
if (_.has(foo, 'bar.baz') && _.size(foo.bar.baz) > 2) {
    // Do something
}
```

That `has` check will always need to be performed before verifying the size of a collection with `size`. As it is, single-level nested collections that do not exist return `0`, as expected, because an `undefined` type cannot be iterated over, but going beyond that single level of nesting will throw a `TypeError` without additional logic, even though it is still true that a non-existent, `undefined` value nested several layers deep cannot be iterated over, either. It would make sense to implicitly check whether a collection passed to `size` exists. Doing this would make the following possible:

```
if (_.size(foo.bar.baz) > 2) {
    // Do something
}
```

I'm aware that `get` can be called with a default fallback, and then that can be wrapped in `size`, but this is for those cases when you don't care to store the value of `foo.bar.baz`, but just want to check if it is iterable.

