As far as I know, it is not possible to perform a `find()` and return a deeply-nested value. 

I've implemented my own version, but it might be nice if this was built in to lodash?

```
// Recusively iterates over elements of `collection`, returning the first element `predicate` returns truthy for.
// The predicate is bound to `thisArg` and invoked with three arguments: `(value, index|key, collection)`.
var findDeepValue = function (collection, predicate, thisArg) {
    var result;

    _.each(collection, function (value) {
        if (_.isObject(value) && !_.isFunction(value)) {
            result = findDeepValue.call(this, value, predicate, thisArg);
        }
        else {
            var isMatch = predicate.apply(thisArg, arguments);
            result = isMatch ? value : undefined;
        }

        if (!_.isUndefined(result)) {
            return false;// break out of the loop early
        }
    }, this);

    return result;
};
```

Floating-point version of _.random implementation has quite a non-trivial overhead (in terms of memory allocation and cpu).

We use lodash for mobile web games, random is often used in time-critical per frame loops. The following test illustrates the problem:
http://jsperf.com/lodash-random

I suggest to consider three options:
- Drop the requirement for _.random to include max (for floating point version only!). In most practical scenarios support for inclusivity of "max" for floating point version really does not worth the overhead. 
- Precompute `delta` part on initialization (though I am not sure I fully followed how it is intended to work).
- At the very least - warn about this quite unexpected characteristic in the documentation. 

``` javascript
if (floating || min % 1 || max % 1) {
        var rand = nativeRandom();
        return nativeMin(min + (rand * (max - min + parseFloat('1e-' + ((rand + '').length - 1)))), max);
}
```

